00:42:24,230 --> 00:42:31,590
world but, oh, well, this is the next best thing. So the take-home message up to this

446
00:42:31,590 --> 00:42:39,500
point is measurement and entanglement are the same phenomenon, and what you will find

447
00:42:39,500 --> 00:42:45,820
in many, many accounts and even some professional accounts, is that they're completely different.

448
00:42:45,820 --> 00:42:50,810
That measurement is this common everyday thing that we can sort of intuitively grasp and

449
00:42:50,810 --> 00:42:57,320
entanglement is the quintessential quantum mystery and in fact they are really the exact

450
00:42:57,320 --> 00:43:02,510
same thing. Now, having come to that realization we can now tell a different story about quantum

451
00:43:02,510 --> 00:43:09,050
mechanics that to my software engineer's mind is much more intuitively pleasing than any

452
00:43:09,050 --> 00:43:15,110
of the other competing alternatives. So Copenhagen is the most popular but as we've seen it,

453
00:43:15,110 --> 00:43:22,920
it's scientifically untenable. There just is no collapse. Their--the next most popular

454
00:43:22,920 --> 00:43:28,280
interpretation is the so-called "many worlds" interpretation where it says that anytime

455
00:43:28,280 --> 00:43:34,630
that a particle can go multiple ways, the entire universe splits and the math actually

456
00:43:34,630 --> 00:43:40,280
supports that, but I personally find that that takes a heavier toll on my intuition

457
00:43:40,280 --> 00:43:44,490
than I'm really willing to concede. There's another thing that nobody's ever heard of

458
00:43:44,490 --> 00:43:48,520
called the "transactional" interpretation by fellow named Cramer at the University of

459
00:43:48,520 --> 00:43:50,940
Washington. Actually, if you're really interested in this stuff, I encourage you to take a look

460
00:43:50,940 --> 00:43:58,050
at because it is kind of interesting. It postulates that the backwards in time solution for Maxwell's

461
00:43:58,050 --> 00:44:03,200
equation are physically real and if you make that assumption then you can explain a lot

462
00:44:03,200 --> 00:44:06,870
of stuff, but I don't have time to get into that. What I want to talk about here is the

463
00:44:06,870 --> 00:44:12,260
quantum information theory which I have dubbed the "zero-worlds" interpretation of quantum

464
00:44:12,260 --> 00:44:17,700
mechanics. It's an extension of classical information theory with complex numbers and

465
00:44:17,700 --> 00:44:22,550
if you run through that math you get some very interesting results. So here is a lightning

466
00:44:22,550 --> 00:44:27,690
introduction to classical information theory. It's the study of this quantity called the

467
00:44:27,690 --> 00:44:33,050
Shannon entropy of a system A, which can be in any one of a number of classical states,

468
00:44:33,050 --> 00:44:37,370
and it's defined as the sum of the probability that the system is in sum state A times the

469
00:44:37,370 --> 00:44:43,040
log of that probability and then you take a negative sign. And intuitively, it's a measure

470
00:44:43,040 --> 00:44:48,860
of the amount of randomness that's in the system A. So just to simplify things for the

471
00:44:48,860 --> 00:44:53,580
purpose of this talk, if the system has an equal probability of being in one of N states,

472
00:44:53,580 --> 00:44:59,500
then the entropy is just the log of N. So when N is one and the system is definitely

473
00:44:59,500 --> 00:45:05,410
in one state then the entropy is zero. And if it can be in one of two states with equal

474
00:45:05,410 --> 00:45:10,770
probability and we take this log base two, we measure information content in bits, then

475
00:45:10,770 --> 00:45:19,550
it has one bit of randomness in it. You can define all kinds of other derived quantities

476
00:45:19,550 --> 00:45:23,770
like the joint entropy of multiple systems and the conditional entropy, and this quantity

477
00:45:23,770 --> 00:45:28,140
here which is called the information entropy which is a measure of how much information

478
00:45:28,140 --> 00:45:32,960
a system A contains about a system B, and the interesting thing to note about it is

479
00:45:32,960 --> 00:45:41,110
it's the sum of some of these other quantities that had been defined up here. And the information

480
00:45:41,110 --> 00:45:46,950
entropy ranges between zero and one, where zero means that this system has no--system

481
00:45:46,950 --> 00:45:51,930
A has no information about system B, they're completely uncorrelated, and one means that

482
00:45:51,930 --> 00:45:58,530
they're perfectly correlated. So for example, because they're sums we can describe these

483
00:45:58,530 --> 00:46:05,730
quantities as Venn diagrams. So this circle here on the left is system A and this circle

484
00:46:05,730 --> 00:46:14,160
on the right is the system B, and the total entropy is contained inside these circles,

485
00:46:14,160 --> 00:46:19,430
the total entropy for each system, and the information entropy is here in the intersection,

486
00:46:19,430 --> 00:46:29,000
and that leaves the conditional entropy out here because the information entropy is the

487
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:36,110
system's individual entropy minus the conditional entropy, just simple addition. This is the

488
00:46:36,110 --> 00:46:40,730
important part. If we flip two coins so that they're completely independent of each other,

489
00:46:40,730 --> 00:46:47,850
this is what the numbers end up looking like. The conditional entropy, the coin A has one

490
00:46:47,850 --> 00:46:51,910
bit of randomness and coin B has one bit of randomness so the total entropy in the system

491
00:46:51,910 --> 00:46:55,970
is two bits of randomness. The system as a whole of these two coins can be in one of

492
00:46:55,970 --> 00:47:02,460
four states, the log of four is two, and there's no information that one coin contains about

493
00:47:02,460 --> 00:47:07,710
the other. By way of contrast, if we have a coin with a sensor, just looking at that

494
00:47:07,710 --> 00:47:13,760
coin telling us whether it's landed heads or tails then--and the sensor is working properly,

495
00:47:13,760 --> 00:47:21,550
then we have one bit of information entropy because the sensor gives us perfect information

496
00:47:21,550 --> 00:47:24,980
about the coin and vice versa by the way. The coin gives us perfect information about

497
00:47:24,980 --> 00:47:29,920
the sensor, there's no directionality here, and the total entropy in the system is one

498
00:47:29,920 --> 00:47:33,720
bit so it's only going to be in one of two states, heads and sensor says heads, or tails

499
00:47:33,720 --> 00:47:41,080
and sensor says tails. If we extend, do the same math again except using complex numbers

500
00:47:41,080 --> 00:47:47,060
instead of real numbers then you end up with something called the Von Neumann entropy which

501
00:47:47,060 --> 00:47:54,530
is called S and this hairy-looking equation over here, which I don't have time to go into,

502
00:47:54,530 --> 00:48:00,170
but the intuition is kind of the same as it was before when we talked about how interference

503
00:48:00,170 --> 00:48:05,480
was produced. Because we're now dealing with complex numbers rather than real numbers,

504
00:48:05,480 --> 00:48:09,740
the information entropy is no longer restricted to the range zero and one. And, in fact, entropies

505
00:48:09,740 --> 00:48:17,470
are no longer restricted to be positive real numbers, they can be negative. And this turns

506
00:48:17,470 --> 00:48:24,410
out to be, if you do the math, the entropy diagram for a pair of entangled particles.

507
00:48:24,410 --> 00:48:30,980
You get a negative bit of entropy over here. And the information entropy, the amount of

508
00:48:30,980 --> 00:48:35,990
information that one particle quantum information now, that one particle contains about the

509
00:48:35,990 --> 00:48:42,320
other is two bits. So you can think about two entangled particles, the math is telling

510
00:48:42,320 --> 00:48:46,730
us that these particles are now, somehow, better than perfectly correlated. They have

511
00:48:46,730 --> 00:48:53,690
become super correlated and the total entropy of this system, the sum of all these numbers,

512
00:48:53,690 --> 00:49:02,230
is zero. There's no randomness. That's not yet the cool part. What happens when we take

513
00:49:02,230 --> 00:49:07,690
a measurement? Well, when we take measurement, we have a particle that becomes entangled

514
00:49:07,690 --> 00:49:12,200
with a macroscopic system of particles. So what happens if we have three mutually entangled

